If you don’t feel a little silly, you’re not doing it right!

And that’s on teaching your expectations the first weeks of school🤪☺️

It wasn’t until I moved down to Kindergarten that I realized how explicit I needed to be with teaching the “how to’s” and expectations to my Kindergarten students. In order to be successful for the entire school year, we’ve got to be thorough about EVERYTHING. 

Check out this video where I walk my students through how we can use our scissors safely, responsibly, and respectfully!

I’ve got a whole blog post for you outlining classroom expectations for a great year in K!  Let me know if you’d like the link or tag a friend to watch this video post below 👇🏼 !

node.text:
Double tap if you believe the language you use with students is important❤️

In order to build a strong sense of identity, students need to feel a sense of belonging.  Does your classroom community provide safety and security to your students? 

Identity is also molded by the ways teachers and other people (classmates, parents, caregivers, etc.) respond to their children.  What kind of language are you using when you speak and listen in the classroom?  Are you paying attention when a student makes an attempt to communicate with you?  Do you acknowledge what students say and do without judgement?

Let’s continue to be mindful about the ways we speak and listen.  Teachers should always use language that is encouraging, supportive, and helpful.  This is how we help our students develop strong feelings of worthiness and value.  This is how we build trust and reaffirm that we believe in them.

There are many opportunities during the school day for teachers to support students in character development.  Class meetings, free play, work time, and routines all offer teachable moments and support teachers in building positive relationships with students.

Building these traits is equally as important as academics.  We want to prepare our children for learning and for life.  We want to support our children in building healthy relationships with themselves and others. 

Schools and homes are both wonderful settings for students to practice skills such as communicating, sharing, and working with others. 

When all adults (educators, parents, and caregivers) come together to do this work, our children’s sense of identity benefits immensely. 

How do you teach character education in your classroom?  Let me know below 👇🏼 or tag a friend who would love to read this post!
